topics.content:
Hey
All! 
Opening Day is upon us! Good luck to all. I am requesting some feedback
on our draft. I scheduled the draft to fall after Spring Training has been
completed and we know more of who is who and what is what. I think that has
been a good thing so far.

The other area of feedback I am interested in, is
the draft itself. Did this year's draft seem long to you? Or was it just I
spent all my money early and had to sit through an hour of not buying
anybody.Do wee need to speed the draft up? 

We had one autodrafter, but
that didn't seem to be as frustratingly disruptive this year as it has been in
previous years. (Except that ONE time when I wanted a player and he bid him
up!!) Was that just my imagination or what? Any body else have an
opinion?

One solution on speeding things up, we could shorten the
nomination time, from 25 seconds to like 15 or 10 seconds. I think we could
even do the first 100 players at 15 seconds, then the rest at 10 seconds.
Cutting 10 seconds per player in the draft of 230 players is 2300 seconds or
almost 40 minutes!!! 

Another solution would be to shorten the time between
bids. Now, there is a 10 (or 8) second clock between bids. If no-one bids
after 8(or 10) seconds, the player is SOLD. We could shorten that a few
seconds, to say 5 seconds, and save another 5-10-15 minutes of draft time. It
would just mean that any manager that wants a player better decide
quickly...we'd have to be on our toes!

Any other ideas or suggestions? We
will take them all into account for next year. Any changes will be announced
at season's end or first thing next year. There will not be any draft day
surprises!

topics.content:
Standard
ESPN RULES apply with the addition of 'THE RP RULE'.

 A reminder, ESPN uses
a soft limit of 200 starts per season. 'Soft Limit' means that on the day when
the 200th start is attained, any and all starts that day will count. Example,
if you have 199 starts accrued and you start 5 SPs on a following day, ALL 5
starts will count and you will end up with 204 starts for the season. After
the day the limit is reached or exceeded, all other starts on following days
will not count.

THE RP RULE: 
We feel there is a small but possible
exploit of RP usage where only a few MLB-active RPs have SP eligibility and
can be used in the SP slots under ESPN rules, thereby giving an owner an
unfair advantage. The rule is an attempt to close this loophole. Please abide
by the INTENT of this rule as any attempt to circumvent this rule with
unforeseen methods will be considered a violation of these rules and you will
be penalized accordingly.

The simple rule for this league is as follows. An
owner is allowed to have only THREE total MLB-active RPs in their active, non-
bench daily slots at any given time.

 An MLB-active RP is defined as a
pitcher who is not in the starting rotation of a team and pitches mostly out
of the bullpen, except for emergency spot starting.

If you have an MLB-
active RP who has ONLY SP eligibility, then you MUST leave an RP slot vacant
on the days that you place this SP-only eligible RP in an SP slot.
 
The
penalty for playing 4 or more MLB-active RPs in active slots on any given day
will be the removal of all points accrued for ALL MLB-ACTIVE RPs IN ACTIVE RP
OR SP SLOTS for that day. Multiple intentional infractions can lead to owner
removal. 

There is NO penalty for a MLB-rotation-active SP who makes a
random relief
appearance.

MSG_BOARD.content:
Standard
ESPN RULES apply with the addition of 'THE RP RULE'.

 A reminder, ESPN uses
a soft limit of 200 starts per season. 'Soft Limit' means that on the day when
the 200th start is attained, any and all starts that day will count. Example,
if you have 199 starts accrued and you start 5 SPs on a following day, ALL 5
starts will count and you will end up with 204 starts for the season. After
the day the limit is reached or exceeded, all other starts on following days
will not count.

THE RP RULE: 
We feel there is a small but possible
exploit of RP usage where only a few MLB-active RPs have SP eligibility and
can be used in the SP slots under ESPN rules, thereby giving an owner an
unfair advantage. The rule is an attempt to close this loophole. Please abide
by the INTENT of this rule as any attempt to circumvent this rule with
unforeseen methods will be considered a violation of these rules and you will
be penalized accordingly.

The simple rule for this league is as follows. An
owner is allowed to have only THREE total MLB-active RPs in their active, non-
bench daily slots at any given time.

 An MLB-active RP is defined as a
pitcher who is not in the starting rotation of a team and pitches mostly out
of the bullpen, except for emergency spot starting.

If you have an MLB-
active RP who has ONLY SP eligibility, then you MUST leave an RP slot vacant
on the days that you place this SP-only eligible RP in an SP slot.
 
The
penalty for playing 4 or more MLB-active RPs in active slots on any given day
will be the removal of all points accrued for ALL MLB-ACTIVE RPs IN ACTIVE RP
OR SP SLOTS for that day. Multiple intentional infractions can lead to owner
removal. 

There is NO penalty for a MLB-rotation-active SP who makes a
random relief
appearance.

Opening Day is upon us! Good luck to all. I am requesting some feedback
on our draft. I scheduled the draft to fall after Spring Training has been
completed and we know more of who is who and what is what. I think that has
been a good thing so far.

The other area of feedback I am interested in, is
the draft itself. Did this year's draft seem long to you? Or was it just I
spent all my money early and had to sit through an hour of not buying
anybody.Do wee need to speed the draft up? 

We had one autodrafter, but
that didn't seem to be as frustratingly disruptive this year as it has been in
previous years. (Except that ONE time when I wanted a player and he bid him
up!!) Was that just my imagination or what? Any body else have an
opinion?

One solution on speeding things up, we could shorten the
nomination time, from 25 seconds to like 15 or 10 seconds. I think we could
even do the first 100 players at 15 seconds, then the rest at 10 seconds.
Cutting 10 seconds per player in the draft of 230 players is 2300 seconds or
almost 40 minutes!!! 

Another solution would be to shorten the time between
